<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-998-426  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 998 426.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Lan Times  Dec 1989 v6 n12 p87(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lawgivers: why is the law having such a hard time creating andenforcing anti-infection laws?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Price, Ron.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Many network users are confused at the seeming inability of thelegal system to take firm action in the prosecution of computerhackers who cause damage by infecting systems with worms andviruses.andP;  Our legal system faces a number of perplexing issues asit seeks to sort out and formulate legal action against theseperpetrators.andP;  First is the difficulty of applying existing legalprinciples and precedents to new categories of crime such ascomputer viruses and worms.andP;  A possible recourse is in tort law,which recognizes a person's right of recovery for damagesinflicted by someone's wrongful conduct, trespass ontointellectual property or conversion of another's property fortheir own use.andP;  This is complicated by the issue of negligence,and by the fact that most hackers lack the financial resources topay extensive damages even if awarded.andP;  Lack of computer knowledgeamong jurists compounds the problem.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Legal IssuesComputer CrimesComputer VirusesData SecurityHuman Factors.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>